# Autonomous Lifecycle Protocol (ALP) Cursor Rules

You are an AI Agent operating within an ALP-managed workspace. 

## 1. Context Discovery
- ALWAYS read `.alp/project.alp` first to understand the context of the repository.
- If I ask you to work on a specific feature, read `.alp/features/<feature-name>.alp` to understand the acceptance criteria and tasks.
- If you need to see the dependency graph of tasks, you can use the `@alp/cli` by running `node cli/dist/index.js graph` in the terminal.

## 2. Working on Tasks
- Tasks are represented as `@task` blocks in `.alp` files.
- Tasks have statuses: `[ ]` (Todo), `[~]` (In Progress), `[x]` (Done), `[!]` (Blocked), `[?]` (Awaiting human review).
- When you begin work on a task, update its status from `[ ]` to `[~]`.
- DO NOT begin work on a task if its blocking dependencies are not `[x]`.

## 3. Completing Work
- When you finish a task, review its `@accept` criteria.
- Run the commands specified in its `@verify` block.
- Only if verification passes, update the task's status to `[x]`.
- Run `node cli/dist/index.js validate` in the terminal to ensure your modifications to `.alp` files did not break the schema or create cyclic dependencies.

## 4. Execution
- Use `node cli/dist/index.js run` to compile the context bundle for the next available task and pipe it into your loop. In swarm mode, `node cli/dist/index.js run --concurrent N` spins up N parallel agents.
- Report progress with `node cli/dist/index.js checkpoint <taskId> <status>` (e.g. `node cli/dist/index.js checkpoint task-login-ui in-progress`). To hand off for human review, use `node cli/dist/index.js checkpoint <taskId> --ask-human "<message>"`, which marks the task `[?]`.
- Never claim a task whose blocking dependencies (`depends_on`, `blocked_by`, `requires`) are not `[x]`. Reference links such as `feature:` or `owner:` do NOT block a task.

## 5. Federation & Supply Chain (V4 → V5)
ALP 4.0.0 adds cross-machine and cross-repository coordination; V5.0.0 hardens the SDK and adds registry signature verification:
- **Networked swarms:** `node cli/dist/index.js swarm join <id>` to join a coordinator; `node cli/dist/index.js run --swarm <id>` executes tasks across machines without double-claiming. Inspect with `node cli/dist/index.js swarm roster <id>`.
- **Cross-repo orchestration:** for `@repo` references, run `node cli/dist/index.js repo resolve --fetch` to merge graphs and resolve `-> repo::object` (read-only). Use `node cli/dist/index.js repo ls` / `node cli/dist/index.js repo graph` to inspect.
- **Policy governance:** honor `@policy` guardrails — pre-check commands/paths with `node cli/dist/index.js policy --command "…"` / `node cli/dist/index.js policy --path "…"`. A strict deny means do NOT perform the action.
- **Registry & packages:** `node cli/dist/index.js registry install @community/<pack>@<range>` to install; `node cli/dist/index.js registry publish ./my-pack` to publish; `node cli/dist/index.js serve --registry` to host.
- **Registry trust & verification:** pin maintainer keys in `.alprc` `trustedKeys` (or via `node cli/dist/index.js keys trust add <ns|*> <fingerprint|file>`); installs are verified automatically. Audit any package — local or remote — with `node cli/dist/index.js registry verify <name>[@version]` and `node cli/dist/index.js registry verify <name>[@version] --url <host>` without installing.
- **Live observability:** `node cli/dist/index.js serve` runs a dashboard (HTTP + SSE) of task status, claims, and analytics.

## 6. Syntax Strictness
- `.alp` files use indentation to represent nesting.
- Block markers like `@project` or `@task` must be at 0 indentation.
- Properties must be indented with exactly 2 spaces.
- Array items (like `- -> task-name`) must be indented with exactly 4 spaces.
- Never use JSON-style objects inside lists. Keep arrays flat.
